ARCHITECTURE.md
     1→# Architecture
     2→
     3→> Document is a work in progress!
     4→
     5→⌘K is born from a simple constraint: can you write a combobox with filtering and sorting using the [compound component](https://kentcdodds.com/blog/compound-components-with-react-hooks) approach? We didn't want to render items manually from an array:
     6→
     7→```tsx
     8→// No
    46→## Approach
    47→
    48→⌘K always keeps every item and group rendered in the React tree. Each item and group adds or removes itself from the DOM based on the search input. The DOM is authoritative. Item selection order is based on the DOM order, which is based on the React render order, which the consumer provides.
    49→
    50→### Discarded approach
    51→
    52→We did not use `React.Children` iteration because it will not support component composition. There is no way to "peek inside" the items contained within `<BlogItems />`, so those items cannot be filtered.
    53→
    54→We did not use an object-based data array for each item, like `{ name: "Logout", action: () => logout() }` because this is strict and limiting. In reality, the interface of those objects grows with edge-cases, like `image`, `detailedSubTitle`, `hideWhenRootSearch`, etc. We prefer that you have full control of item rendering, including icons, keyboard shortcuts, and styling. Don't want an item shown? Don't render it. Only want to show an item under condition xyz? Render it.
    55→
    56→We did not use a render prop because they are an inelegant pattern and quickly fall to long, centralised if-else logic chains. For example, if you want a fancy sparkle rainbow item, you need a new if statement to render that item specially.
    57→
    60→## Example
    61→
    62→```tsx
    63→<Input value="b" />
    64→<List>
    65→  <Item>A</Item>
    66→  <Item>B</Item>
    67→</List>
    92→## Performance
    93→
    94→This is more expensive memory wise, because if there are 2,000 items but the list is filtered to only 2 items, we still allocate memory for 2,000 instances of the Item component. But it's our only option! Thankfully we can still keep the DOM size to 2 items.
    95→
    96→## Groups
    97→
    98→Item mount informs both the root and the parent group, which keeps track of items within it. Each group informs the root.
README.md
     5→# ⌘K [![cmdk minzip package size](https://img.shields.io/bundlephobia/minzip/cmdk)](https://www.npmjs.com/package/cmdk?activeTab=code) [![cmdk package version](https://img.shields.io/npm/v/cmdk.svg?colorB=green)](https://www.npmjs.com/package/cmdk)
     6→
     7→⌘K is a command menu React component that can also be used as an accessible combobox. You render items, it filters and sorts them automatically. ⌘K supports a fully composable API <sup><sup>[How?](/ARCHITECTURE.md)</sup></sup>, so you can wrap items in other components or even as static JSX.
     8→
     9→## Install
    10→
    11→```bash
    12→pnpm install cmdk
    13→```
    14→
    15→## Use
    16→
    17→```tsx
    18→import { Command } from 'cmdk'
    19→
    20→const CommandMenu = () => {
    21→  return (
    22→    <Command label="Command Menu">
    82→## Parts and styling
    83→
    84→All parts forward props, including `ref`, to an appropriate element. Each part has a specific data-attribute (starting with `cmdk-`) that can be used for styling.
    85→
    86→### Command `[cmdk-root]`
    87→
    88→Render this to show the command menu inline, or use [Dialog](#dialog-cmdk-dialog-cmdk-overlay) to render in a elevated context. Can be controlled with the `value` and `onValueChange` props.
    89→
    90→> **Note**
    91→>
    92→> Values are always trimmed with the [trim()](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/String/trim) method.
    93→
   153→### Dialog `[cmdk-dialog]` `[cmdk-overlay]`
   154→
   155→Props are forwarded to [Command](#command-cmdk-root). Composes Radix UI's Dialog component. The overlay is always rendered. See the [Radix Documentation](https://www.radix-ui.com/docs/primitives/components/dialog) for more information. Can be controlled with the `open` and `onOpenChange` props.
   156→
   157→```tsx
   158→const [open, setOpen] = React.useState(false)
   159→
   160→return (
   180→### Input `[cmdk-input]`
   181→
   182→All props are forwarded to the underlying `input` element. Can be controlled with the `value` and `onValueChange` props.
   183→
   184→```tsx
   185→const [search, setSearch] = React.useState('')
   186→
   187→return <Command.Input value={search} onValueChange={setSearch} />
   190→### List `[cmdk-list]`
   191→
   192→Contains items and groups. Animate height using the `--cmdk-list-height` CSS variable.
   193→
   194→```css
   195→[cmdk-list] {
   196→  min-height: 300px;
   197→  height: var(--cmdk-list-height);
   212→### Item `[cmdk-item]` `[data-disabled?]` `[data-selected?]`
   213→
   214→Item that becomes active on pointer enter. You should provide a unique `value` for each item, but it will be automatically inferred from the `.textContent`.
   215→
   216→```tsx
   217→<Command.Item
   218→  onSelect={(value) => console.log('Selected', value)}
   219→  // Value is implicity "apple" because of the provided text content
   242→### Group `[cmdk-group]` `[hidden?]`
   243→
   244→Groups items together with the given `heading` (`[cmdk-group-heading]`).
   245→
   246→```tsx
   247→<Command.Group heading="Fruit">
   248→  <Command.Item>Apple</Command.Item>
   249→</Command.Group>
   256→### Separator `[cmdk-separator]`
   257→
   258→Visible when the search query is empty or `alwaysRender` is true, hidden otherwise.
   259→
   260→### Empty `[cmdk-empty]`
   261→
   262→Automatically renders when there are no results for the search query.
   263→
   264→### Loading `[cmdk-loading]`
   265→
   266→You should conditionally render this with `progress` while loading asynchronous items.
   267→
   268→```tsx
   269→const [loading, setLoading] = React.useState(false)
   270→
   271→return <Command.List>{loading && <Command.Loading>Hang on…</Command.Loading>}</Command.List>
   274→### `useCommandState(state => state.selectedField)`
   275→
   276→Hook that composes [`useSyncExternalStore`](https://reactjs.org/docs/hooks-reference.html#usesyncexternalstore). Pass a function that returns a slice of the command menu state to re-render when that slice changes. This hook is provided for advanced use cases and should not be commonly used.
   277→
   278→A good use case would be to render a more detailed empty state, like so:
   279→
   280→```tsx
   281→const search = useCommandState((state) => state.search)
   285→## Examples
   286→
   287→Code snippets for common use cases.
   288→
   289→### Nested items
   290→
   291→Often selecting one item should navigate deeper, with a more refined set of items. For example selecting "Change theme…" should show new items "Dark theme" and "Light theme". We call these sets of items "pages", and they can be implemented with simple state:
   292→
   293→```tsx
   294→const ref = React.useRef(null)
   295→const [open, setOpen] = React.useState(false)
   296→const [search, setSearch] = React.useState('')
   338→### Show sub-items when searching
   339→
   340→If your items have nested sub-items that you only want to reveal when searching, render based on the search state:
   341→
   342→```tsx
   343→const SubItem = (props) => {
   344→  const search = useCommandState((state) => state.search)
   345→  if (!search) return null
   361→### Asynchronous results
   362→
   363→Render the items as they become available. Filtering and sorting will happen automatically.
   364→
   365→```tsx
   366→const [loading, setLoading] = React.useState(false)
   367→const [items, setItems] = React.useState([])
   368→
   397→### Use inside Popover
   398→
   399→We recommend using the [Radix UI popover](https://www.radix-ui.com/docs/primitives/components/popover) component. ⌘K relies on the Radix UI Dialog component, so this will reduce your bundle size a bit due to shared dependencies.
   400→
   401→```bash
   402→$ pnpm install @radix-ui/react-popover
   403→```
   404→
   426→### Drop in stylesheets
   427→
   428→You can find global stylesheets to drop in as a starting point for styling. See [website/styles/cmdk](website/styles/cmdk) for examples.
   429→
   430→## FAQ
   431→
   432→**Accessible?** Yes. Labeling, aria attributes, and DOM ordering tested with Voice Over and Chrome DevTools. [Dialog](#dialog-cmdk-dialog-cmdk-overlay) composes an accessible Dialog implementation.
   433→
   434→**Virtualization?** No. Good performance up to 2,000-3,000 items, though. Read below to bring your own.
   435→
   436→**Filter/sort items manually?** Yes. Pass `shouldFilter={false}` to [Command](#command-cmdk-root). Better memory usage and performance. Bring your own virtualization this way.
   437→
   456→## History
   457→
   458→Written in 2019 by Paco ([@pacocoursey](https://twitter.com/pacocoursey)) to see if a composable combobox API was possible. Used for the Vercel command menu and autocomplete by Rauno ([@raunofreiberg](https://twitter.com/raunofreiberg)) in 2020. Re-written independently in 2022 with a simpler and more performant approach. Ideas and help from Shu ([@shuding\_](https://twitter.com/shuding_)).
   459→
   460→[use-descendants](https://github.com/pacocoursey/use-descendants) was extracted from the 2019 version.
   461→
   462→## Testing
   463→
   464→First, install dependencies and Playwright browsers:
   465→
   466→```bash
   467→pnpm install
   468→pnpm playwright install
   469→```
